# split balance into categorical - 3 bins Negative balance = 0, 0-5000 dollars =1, greater than 5000 dollars = 2

Get data ready for Modeling¶

In [25]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix,accuracy_score,f1_score,recall_score,precision_score,roc_auc_score
In [26]:
y = df['Target_yes']
X = df.drop('Target_yes', axis=1)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

Make a dataframe to compare Model results¶

In [27]:
colnames = ['Model Type','Accuracy','Precision','Recall','F1']
compDF = pd.DataFrame(columns=colnames)

Create Models¶

Logistic Regression¶

In [28]:
logreg = LogisticRegression(random_state=100, max_iter=1000)
logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[28]:
LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=100)
In [29]:
#check accuracy of training model
lr_trainscore = logreg.score(X_train, y_train)
print("Accuracy of Logistic Regression Training Model is: "+(str(lr_trainscore)))

Accuracy of Logistic Regression Training Model is: 0.8812841659556988
In [30]:
lr_predict = logreg.predict(X_test)
lr_acc = logreg.score(X_test, y_test)
lr_prec = precision_score(y_test, lr_predict)
lr_recall = recall_score(y_test, lr_predict)
lr_f1 = f1_score(y_test, lr_predict)
compDF = compDF.append(dict(zip(colnames, ["Logistic Regression",lr_acc,lr_prec,lr_recall,lr_f1])), ignore_index=True)
compDF

Why is the Recall Score so low?? For the model to be useful, this needs to be much higher, because we want to minimize False Negatives (which represent missed customers).
